# Jest Testing Framework Architecture

## Core Principles

### Framework Foundation
- **Jest as Primary Framework**: Use Jest for unit, integration, and snapshot testing
- **TypeScript Support**: Leverage ts-jest for TypeScript projects
- **Modular Test Structure**: Organize tests by feature or component
- **Clear Naming**: Use descriptive test names that explain behavior

## Project Structure

```
project/
├── src/
│   ├── components/
│   │   ├── Button.ts
│   │   └── Button.test.ts
│   ├── services/
│   │   ├── api.ts
│   │   └── api.test.ts
│   └── utils/
│       ├── helpers.ts
│       └── helpers.test.ts
├── __tests__/
│   ├── integration/
│   └── e2e/
├── __mocks__/
│   ├── fileMock.js
│   └── styleMock.js
├── jest.config.js
└── jest.setup.js
```

## Test File Organization

### Naming Conventions
```javascript
// ✅ Good
Button.test.ts          // Component tests
userService.test.ts     // Service tests
formatDate.test.ts      // Utility tests

// ❌ Avoid
Button.spec.ts          // Use .test.ts for consistency
test_button.ts          // Use camelCase, not snake_case
ButtonTest.ts           // Don't capitalize Test
```

### Test Structure Pattern (AAA Pattern)
```javascript
describe('ComponentName or FunctionName', () => {
  // Arrange - Setup
  beforeEach(() => {
    // Common setup
  });

  afterEach(() => {
    // Cleanup
  });

  test('should describe expected behavior', () => {
    // Arrange - Prepare test data
    const input = 'test';

    // Act - Execute the code
    const result = functionUnderTest(input);

    // Assert - Verify results
    expect(result).toBe('expected');
  });
});
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Descriptive Test Names
```javascript
// ✅ Good - Behavior-driven descriptions
test('should return user data when API call succeeds', () => {});
test('should throw error when user is not found', () => {});
test('should disable button when form is invalid', () => {});

// ❌ Avoid - Vague descriptions
test('works correctly', () => {});
test('test 1', () => {});
test('returns data', () => {});
```

### 2. Group Related Tests
```javascript
describe('UserService', () => {
  describe('getUser', () => {
    test('should return user when found', () => {});
    test('should return null when not found', () => {});
    test('should handle network errors', () => {});
  });

  describe('createUser', () => {
    test('should create user with valid data', () => {});
    test('should validate email format', () => {});
    test('should reject duplicate emails', () => {});
  });
});
```

### 3. Use Setup and Teardown Hooks
```javascript
describe('Database operations', () => {
  let db;

  // Runs once before all tests
  beforeAll(async () => {
    db = await connectDatabase();
  });

  // Runs before each test
  beforeEach(async () => {
    await db.clear();
  });

  // Runs after each test
  afterEach(async () => {
    await db.cleanup();
  });

  // Runs once after all tests
  afterAll(async () => {
    await db.disconnect();
  });

  test('should save data', () => {});
});
```

### 4. Avoid Test Interdependence
```javascript
// ✅ Good - Each test is independent
describe('Counter', () => {
  test('should start at 0', () => {
    const counter = new Counter();
    expect(counter.value).toBe(0);
  });

  test('should increment by 1', () => {
    const counter = new Counter();
    counter.increment();
    expect(counter.value).toBe(1);
  });
});

// ❌ Avoid - Tests depend on each other
describe('Counter', () => {
  const counter = new Counter(); // Shared state!

  test('should start at 0', () => {
    expect(counter.value).toBe(0);
  });

  test('should increment by 1', () => {
    counter.increment(); // Depends on previous test
    expect(counter.value).toBe(1);
  });
});
```

## Common Matchers

### Basic Matchers
```javascript
expect(value).toBe(4);                    // Strict equality (===)
expect(value).toEqual({ name: 'John' });  // Deep equality
expect(value).not.toBe(null);             // Negation
expect(value).toBeTruthy();               // Truthy check
expect(value).toBeFalsy();                // Falsy check
expect(value).toBeUndefined();            // Undefined check
expect(value).toBeDefined();              // Defined check
expect(value).toBeNull();                 // Null check
```

### Number Matchers
```javascript
expect(value).toBeGreaterThan(3);
expect(value).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(3.5);
expect(value).toBeLessThan(5);
expect(value).toBeLessThanOrEqual(4.5);
expect(value).toBeCloseTo(0.3);           // Floating point
```

### String Matchers
```javascript
expect(text).toMatch(/pattern/);
expect(text).toContain('substring');
expect(text).toHaveLength(10);
```

### Array/Object Matchers
```javascript
expect(array).toContain('item');
expect(array).toHaveLength(3);
expect(obj).toHaveProperty('key', 'value');
expect(obj).toMatchObject({ name: 'John' });
```

### Function Matchers
```javascript
expect(fn).toThrow();
expect(fn).toThrow('error message');
expect(fn).toThrow(Error);
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith(arg1, arg2);
```

## Async Testing

### Using async/await
```javascript
test('should fetch user data', async () => {
  const user = await fetchUser(1);
  expect(user.name).toBe('John');
});
```

### Using Promises
```javascript
test('should fetch user data', () => {
  return fetchUser(1).then(user => {
    expect(user.name).toBe('John');
  });
});
```

### Using resolves/rejects
```javascript
test('should fetch user data', async () => {
  await expect(fetchUser(1)).resolves.toEqual({ name: 'John' });
});

test('should handle errors', async () => {
  await expect(fetchUser(-1)).rejects.toThrow('User not found');
});
```

## Performance Guidelines

### 1. Keep Tests Fast
- Mock external dependencies (API calls, database)
- Use in-memory databases for testing
- Avoid unnecessary setup/teardown

### 2. Run Tests in Parallel
```javascript
// jest.config.js
module.exports = {
  maxWorkers: '50%', // Use 50% of available CPU cores
};
```

### 3. Use Test Filtering
```bash
# Run specific test file
npm test Button.test.ts

# Run tests matching pattern
npm test -- --testNamePattern="should render"

# Run only changed tests
npm test -- --onlyChanged
```

## Code Coverage

### Configuration
```javascript
// jest.config.js
module.exports = {
  collectCoverage: true,
  coverageDirectory: 'coverage',
  coverageReporters: ['text', 'lcov', 'html'],
  coverageThreshold: {
    global: {
      branches: 80,
      functions: 80,
      lines: 80,
      statements: 80,
    },
  },
};
```

### Run Coverage
```bash
npm test -- --coverage
```

## Error Handling

### Test Error Cases
```javascript
test('should throw error for invalid input', () => {
  expect(() => {
    divide(10, 0);
  }).toThrow('Cannot divide by zero');
});

test('should handle API errors', async () => {
  const mockError = new Error('Network error');
  mockFetch.mockRejectedValue(mockError);

  await expect(fetchData()).rejects.toThrow('Network error');
});
```

## Documentation

### Add Comments for Complex Tests
```javascript
test('should calculate compound interest correctly', () => {
  // Formula: A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)
  // P = 1000 (principal)
  // r = 0.05 (5% annual rate)
  // n = 12 (monthly compounding)
  // t = 2 (years)
  const result = calculateCompoundInterest(1000, 0.05, 12, 2);

  expect(result).toBeCloseTo(1104.94, 2);
});
```

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

### ❌ Don't Test Implementation Details
```javascript
// ❌ Bad - Testing internal state
test('should set isLoading to true', () => {
  component.fetchData();
  expect(component.isLoading).toBe(true);
});

// ✅ Good - Testing behavior
test('should show loading spinner while fetching', () => {
  render(<Component />);
  expect(screen.getByText('Loading...')).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

### ❌ Don't Write Overly Complex Tests
```javascript
// ❌ Bad - Too much logic in test
test('complex test', () => {
  const data = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    data.push(processItem(i));
  }
  expect(data.filter(x => x > 5).length).toBe(4);
});

// ✅ Good - Simple and clear
test('should process items greater than 5', () => {
  const result = processItems([1, 6, 7, 8]);
  expect(result).toEqual([6, 7, 8]);
});
```

### ❌ Don't Duplicate Production Code
```javascript
// ❌ Bad - Reimplementing the same logic
test('should calculate total', () => {
  const items = [{ price: 10 }, { price: 20 }];
  const total = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
  expect(calculateTotal(items)).toBe(total); // Same logic!
});

// ✅ Good - Test with known values
test('should calculate total', () => {
  const items = [{ price: 10 }, { price: 20 }];
  expect(calculateTotal(items)).toBe(30);
});
```

## CI/CD Integration

### GitHub Actions Example
```yaml
- name: Run tests
  run: npm test -- --ci --coverage --maxWorkers=2

- name: Upload coverage
  uses: codecov/codecov-action@v3
  with:
    files: ./coverage/lcov.info
```

## Quick Reference

### Essential Commands
```bash
npm test                          # Run all tests
npm test -- --watch              # Watch mode
npm test -- --coverage           # With coverage
npm test Button.test.ts          # Specific file
npm test -- --testNamePattern="render"  # Pattern match
npm test -- --onlyChanged        # Only changed files
npm test -- --updateSnapshot     # Update snapshots
```

### Key Concepts
- **Describe blocks**: Group related tests
- **Test blocks**: Individual test cases
- **Matchers**: Assertion methods (expect)
- **Mocks**: Replace dependencies
- **Spies**: Track function calls
- **Snapshots**: Capture component output
- **Coverage**: Measure tested code
